{{define "content"}}<main class="gw-page">
  <section class="gw-card gw-docs-intro">
    <h1 class="gw-h2">Documentation</h1>
    <p>Operator reference for the Gateway binary. For live status see <a href="/admin/">Dashboard</a>; for build metadata see <a href="/admin/about">About</a>. This page is a server-rendered snapshot of the running configuration — it does NOT auto-refresh.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Environment variables</h2>
    <p>Current values reflect the configuration in effect at server start. Sensitive values (bearer token, allowlist) are summarised as <code>(set)</code> / <code>(unset)</code>. Rows whose current value is <code>(see startup log)</code> are not yet surfaced in the admin runtime snapshot.</p>
    <div class="gw-docs-table-scroll">
      <table class="gw-table gw-docs-env-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th scope="col">Variable</th><th scope="col">Default</th><th scope="col">Description</th><th scope="col">Current value</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{range .EnvVars}}
          <tr>
            <td><code>{{.Name}}</code></td>
            <td>{{.Default}}</td>
            <td>{{.Description}}</td>
            <td class="current"><code>{{.CurrentValue}}</code></td>
          </tr>
          {{end}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Files &amp; paths</h2>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Install anchors</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt>Config (<code>GW_HOME</code>)</dt><dd><code>$HOME/.gw</code> (POSIX) / <code>$env:USERPROFILE\.gw</code> (Windows) — precious; <code>.env</code>, <code>overrides.env</code>, logs, state. Never overwritten on upgrade.</dd>
      <dt>Code (<code>GW_INSTALL_DIR</code>)</dt><dd>Per-OS default — <code>~/Library/Application Support/Gateway</code> (macOS), <code>${XDG_DATA_HOME:-~/.local/share}/gateway</code> (Linux), <code>%LOCALAPPDATA%\Gateway</code> (Windows) — binary + wrapper scripts. Replaceable on upgrade.</dd>
      <dt>Override</dt><dd>Set <code>GW_HOME</code> / <code>GW_INSTALL_DIR</code> to relocate either anchor independently.</dd>
    </dl>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Env files (loaded by the wrapper on every invocation)</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt>User env (POSIX)</dt><dd><code>$GW_HOME/.env</code> — default <code>$HOME/.gw/.env</code></dd>
      <dt>User env (Windows)</dt><dd><code>$GW_HOME\.env</code> — default <code>$env:USERPROFILE\.gw\.env</code></dd>
      <dt>Project env</dt><dd><code>./.env</code> (relative to cwd; checked before the user env above)</dd>
      <dt>User overrides</dt><dd><code>$GW_HOME/overrides.env</code> — operator-owned; loaded last, wins on shared keys</dd>
      <dt>Project overrides</dt><dd><code>./overrides.env</code> (relative to cwd; checked before the user overrides above)</dd>
    </dl>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Runtime files</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt>Chat trace file</dt><dd><code>{{.ChatTraceFile}}</code>{{if not .ChatTraceEnabled}} <span class="gw-badge">disabled</span>{{end}}</dd>
      <dt>Chat trace retention</dt><dd>{{.ChatTraceMaxAgeDays}} days (timberjack MaxAge)</dd>
      <dt>Admin static assets</dt><dd>Embedded in the binary via <code>embed.FS</code> (no on-disk lookup at runtime).</dd>
      <dt>Wrapper env files</dt><dd><code>.env</code> (generated template; load-first) then <code>overrides.env</code> (operator-owned secrets/customisations; load-second wins). See <code>scripts/gw upgrade-env</code>.</dd>
      <dt>Log destination</dt><dd>Structured slog JSON to stdout/stderr by default. Set <code>LOG_FILE</code> to also write a rotated file.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">CLI &amp; startup (gw wrapper)</h2>
    <p>Operators interact with the gateway through the <code>gw</code> wrapper rather than the <code>gateway</code> binary directly. PowerShell uses PascalCase switches (<code>-Trace</code>, <code>-Debug</code>); POSIX uses kebab-case (<code>--trace</code>, <code>--debug</code>). The <code>.bat</code> dispatcher just forwards args to PowerShell — same switch syntax.</p>
    <p>Run <code>gw -h</code> / <code>gw --help</code> (POSIX) or <code>gw.ps1 -Help</code> (PowerShell) at any time to print the full usage to your terminal.</p>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">macOS / Linux (POSIX)</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">./scripts/gw init --non-interactive       # write $GW_HOME/.env from template
./scripts/gw start                         # background daemon (writes PID file)
./scripts/gw start --pii encrypt --encrypt-key &lt;key&gt; --auth &lt;token&gt;
./scripts/gw status                        # /admin/api/snapshot summary
./scripts/gw logs -f                       # tail the rotated structured log
./scripts/gw restart --idle-timeout 60
./scripts/gw stop                          # SIGTERM + reap stray kiro-cli orphans
./scripts/gw run --trace                   # foreground; DEBUG=true + CHAT_TRACE=true
./scripts/gw env --show-secrets            # dump resolved env (secrets visible)
./scripts/gw upgrade-env --dry-run         # diff template vs. installed env file
./scripts/gw migrate-to-overrides --yes    # one-time split into overrides file
./scripts/gw version                       # delegates to the binary --version</pre>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Windows (PowerShell)</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">.\scripts\gw.ps1 init -NonInteractive
.\scripts\gw.ps1 start
.\scripts\gw.ps1 start -Pii encrypt -EncryptKey &lt;key&gt; -Auth &lt;token&gt;
.\scripts\gw.ps1 status
.\scripts\gw.ps1 logs -Follow
.\scripts\gw.ps1 restart -IdleTimeout 60
.\scripts\gw.ps1 stop
.\scripts\gw.ps1 run -Trace
.\scripts\gw.ps1 env -ShowSecrets
.\scripts\gw.ps1 upgrade-env -DryRun
.\scripts\gw.ps1 migrate-to-overrides -Yes
.\scripts\gw.ps1 version</pre>
    <p>Subcommand surface (identical on both wrappers): <code>init</code>, <code>start</code>, <code>stop</code>, <code>restart</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>logs</code>, <code>run</code>, <code>env</code>, <code>upgrade-env</code>, <code>migrate-to-overrides</code>, <code>version</code>.</p>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Picking up new env vars after an upgrade</h3>
    <p>Installing a new gateway build <strong>preserves your existing <code>.env</code></strong> — it does not add newly-introduced keys (e.g. <code>KIRO_TOOL_ALIASES</code>). Because of the two-file model, the generated <code>.env</code> is a byte-for-byte copy of the <code>.env.example</code> template and <code>overrides.env</code> is operator-owned and loaded last (wins on shared keys). To reconcile after an upgrade:</p>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">gw upgrade-env --dry-run    # diff installed .env against the new template
                            #   -> reports added / orphaned / unchanged keys
gw upgrade-env              # regenerate .env from the template (prompts unless --yes)
                            #   orphaned keys are logged to $GW_HOME/upgrade.log first</pre>
    <p><code>upgrade-env</code> never touches <code>overrides.env</code>. Set real deployment values there so they survive every upgrade — e.g. append <code>KIRO_TOOL_ALIASES=execute:run_shell,shell:run_shell</code> to <code>$GW_HOME/overrides.env</code>, then <code>gw restart</code>. Env values also load from the process environment, so the template entry is primarily for discoverability; an unset var falls back to its default (for <code>KIRO_TOOL_ALIASES</code>, no aliases).</p>
    <h3 class="gw-h3">Flag &harr; switch reference</h3>
    <table class="gw-table gw-docs-flags-table gw-flag-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">POSIX flag</th><th scope="col">PowerShell switch</th><th scope="col">Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>--pii MODE</code></td><td><code>-Pii MODE</code></td><td>PII redaction mode (<code>off</code>, <code>replace</code>, <code>mask</code>, <code>hash</code>, <code>drop</code>, <code>encrypt</code>). <code>off</code> sets <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false</code>; any other value enables redaction with that mode.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--hash-key KEY</code></td><td><code>-HashKey KEY</code></td><td>Sets <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>. Required when <code>--pii hash</code> / <code>-Pii hash</code> is in effect.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--encrypt-key KEY</code></td><td><code>-EncryptKey KEY</code></td><td>Sets <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code>. Required when <code>--pii encrypt</code> / <code>-Pii encrypt</code> is in effect (the default), or any <code>PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS</code> entry uses <code>:encrypt</code>. Any non-empty string — the gateway derives a 32-byte AES-256-GCM key via SHA-256 at boot. <code>gw init</code> auto-mints one; <code>--regenerate-secrets</code> rotates it alongside <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> and <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--entities LIST</code></td><td><code>-Entities LIST</code></td><td>Comma-split <code>PII_ENABLED_ENTITIES</code> allowlist (e.g. <code>Email,SSN,PERSON</code>). Empty = all registered recognizers (13 regex + 2 NER when <code>PII_NER_ENABLED=true</code>).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--hooks LIST</code></td><td><code>-Hooks LIST</code></td><td>Comma-split <code>ENABLED_HOOKS</code> allowlist. Empty = all hooks in the chain enabled.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--auth TOKEN</code></td><td><code>-Auth TOKEN</code></td><td>Sets <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> for bearer-token auth.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--idle-timeout SEC</code></td><td><code>-IdleTimeout SEC</code></td><td>Sets <code>STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC</code> (0 disables the watchdog; negative is a boot error).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--env-file PATH</code></td><td><code>-EnvFile PATH</code></td><td>Override the resolved primary <code>.env</code> path.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--overrides-file PATH</code></td><td><code>-OverridesFile PATH</code></td><td>Override the resolved <code>overrides.env</code> path (loaded second; wins on shared keys).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--template PATH</code></td><td><code>-Template PATH</code></td><td>Override the <code>.env.example</code> template used by <code>init</code> / <code>upgrade-env</code> / <code>migrate-to-overrides</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--dest PATH</code></td><td><code>-Dest PATH</code></td><td>Override the destination <code>.env</code> path for <code>init</code> / <code>upgrade-env</code> / <code>migrate-to-overrides</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--overrides-dest PATH</code></td><td><code>-OverridesDest PATH</code></td><td>Override the destination overrides path for <code>migrate-to-overrides</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--dry-run</code></td><td><code>-DryRun</code></td><td>Preview a write-side subcommand (<code>upgrade-env</code>, <code>migrate-to-overrides</code>) without modifying disk.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--yes</code></td><td><code>-Yes</code></td><td>Skip confirmation prompts (CI-friendly).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--show-secrets</code></td><td><code>-ShowSecrets</code></td><td>For the <code>env</code> subcommand: print resolved env including secrets (default is masked).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--debug</code></td><td><code>-Debug</code></td><td>Set <code>DEBUG=true</code> for verbose slog output. PowerShell's <code>-Debug</code> is the built-in common parameter; the wrapper detects it and flips the gateway accordingly.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--trace</code></td><td><code>-Trace</code></td><td>Set <code>DEBUG=true</code> AND <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code> in one go. SENSITIVE: writes raw prompts to <code>CHAT_TRACE_FILE</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>—</td><td><code>-Follow</code></td><td>PowerShell-only: <code>logs -Follow</code> is the equivalent of POSIX <code>logs -f</code> (positional, not a flag on POSIX).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--here</code></td><td><code>-Here</code></td><td><code>init</code> shortcut: write the env file into the current directory instead of <code>$HOME</code> / <code>$env:USERPROFILE</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--force</code></td><td><code>-Force</code></td><td><code>init</code>: overwrite existing dest. Combine with <code>--regenerate-secrets</code> to mint new <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> / <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code> / <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--non-interactive</code></td><td><code>-NonInteractive</code></td><td><code>init</code>: never prompt; use defaults for anything unset.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--auth-enabled</code></td><td><code>-AuthEnabled</code></td><td><code>init</code>: enable bearer-token auth (default off; mints <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> if no <code>--auth-token</code> supplied).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--chat-trace</code></td><td><code>-ChatTrace</code></td><td><code>init</code>: enable chat-trace NDJSON tracer (default off; writes raw prompts to disk).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--regenerate-secrets</code></td><td><code>-RegenerateSecrets</code></td><td><code>init --force</code>: mint new <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code>, <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>, and <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code> even when prior values exist. Rotating <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code> invalidates every prior round-trip token — treat as a breaking change for in-flight encrypted conversations.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--auth-token TOK</code></td><td><code>-AuthToken TOK</code></td><td><code>init</code>: use <code>TOK</code> instead of generating; implies <code>--auth-enabled</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--kiro PATH</code></td><td><code>-Kiro PATH</code></td><td><code>init</code>: <code>KIRO_CMD</code> value (otherwise auto-detected on PATH).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--addr ADDR</code></td><td><code>-Addr ADDR</code></td><td><code>init</code>: <code>HTTP_ADDR</code> value (default <code>127.0.0.1:18080</code>).</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Upgrading</h2>
    <p>Gateway uses a <strong>two-file env model</strong> so upgrades absorb new template defaults without clobbering your secrets. The generated <code>.env</code> file is rewritten from the template on every upgrade. Your <code>overrides.env</code> file is operator-owned, loaded last, and is NEVER touched by <code>upgrade-env</code> or <code>init</code> — its values win on shared keys.</p>

    <p><strong>Do not delete <code>.env</code> to "start fresh".</strong> Deleting it means <code>init</code> mints a brand-new <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> and rotates <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>, breaking any existing auth setup and invalidating prior hash-mode correlation tokens. Use the proper upgrade flow below — it preserves existing secrets by default.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Three-step upgrade flow</h3>
    <ol class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Pull the new install</strong> — fetches the v1.8.2 (or later) binary, template, and wrapper scripts.</li>
      <li><strong>Preview the diff</strong> — <code>upgrade-env --dry-run</code> reports which template keys would be added, orphaned, or unchanged in your env file. No disk writes.</li>
      <li><strong>Apply</strong> — re-run <code>init --force --non-interactive</code>. Existing secrets (<code>AUTH_TOKEN</code>, <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>, <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code>) are <em>preserved across re-init</em>; missing ones are minted; new env vars (e.g., <code>PII_NER_ENABLED</code>) are added with template defaults. Restart to apply.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">macOS / Linux (POSIX)</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cmetech/otto-gateway/main/scripts/install.sh | sh
gw upgrade-env --dry-run             # 1. preview
gw init --force --non-interactive    # 2. absorb new defaults; mint missing keys
gw restart                            # 3. apply</pre>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Windows (PowerShell)</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">irm https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cmetech/otto-gateway/main/scripts/install.ps1 | iex
gw.ps1 upgrade-env -DryRun           # 1. preview
gw.ps1 init -Force -NonInteractive   # 2. absorb new defaults; mint missing keys
gw.ps1 restart                        # 3. apply</pre>
    <p>The <code>.bat</code> dispatcher forwards arguments to PowerShell, so <code>gw init -Force -NonInteractive</code> works the same from <code>cmd.exe</code>.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Preserve vs. rotate secrets</h3>
    <p>The default behavior of <code>init --force</code> is <strong>preserve</strong> — your existing <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code>, <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>, and <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code> are carried across the upgrade verbatim. Add <code>--regenerate-secrets</code> (POSIX) or <code>-RegenerateSecrets</code> (PowerShell) to discard the existing values and mint fresh ones:</p>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">gw init --force --non-interactive --regenerate-secrets    # POSIX
gw.ps1 init -Force -NonInteractive -RegenerateSecrets     # PowerShell</pre>
    <p><strong>Rotating <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code> is a breaking change for in-flight encrypted conversations</strong> — every prior <code>[PII:Entity:base64url(...)]</code> token becomes undecryptable. Only rotate it intentionally (suspected key leak, routine secret rotation, etc.). Rotating <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code> invalidates prior hash-mode correlation tokens — the same correlation-break-on-purpose property.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Upgrading from v1.8.1 → v1.8.2 specifically</h3>
    <p>v1.8.2 flipped three PII defaults to make the gateway secure-by-default. If your existing env file was generated by v1.8.1 or earlier, the dry-run will show:</p>
    <ul class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Added</strong>: <code>PII_NER_ENABLED</code> (default <code>true</code>) — prose-based PERSON / LOCATION recognizer is now on out of the box. The ~7 MB prose model is baked into the binary either way; this flag only controls the runtime allocation. Set to <code>false</code> if you do not want NER active.</li>
      <li><strong>Default change</strong>: <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED</code> flips from <code>false</code> → <code>true</code>. The hook does work by default now.</li>
      <li><strong>Default change</strong>: <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE</code> flips from <code>replace</code> → <code>encrypt</code>. PII flows to the worker as AES-256-GCM ciphertext and is decrypted back to plaintext before the client sees the response (round-trip).</li>
      <li><strong>Auto-mint</strong>: <code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code> is now generated by <code>init</code> alongside <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> and <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>. If your env file already had a value, it is preserved across re-init.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If you want to opt out of the new defaults entirely (stay on the v1.8.1 behavior), put these overrides in <code>overrides.env</code>:</p>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false
PII_REDACTION_MODE=replace
PII_NER_ENABLED=false</pre>
    <p>The overrides file is loaded last, so its values win — and <code>upgrade-env</code> / <code>init</code> never touch it.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">When to keep the file vs. nuke it</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt>Keep the file (recommended)</dt><dd>Use <code>gw init --force --non-interactive</code>. Existing secrets carry across; new env vars get template defaults. No restart-without-auth window.</dd>
      <dt>Nuke <code>.env</code> only when</dt><dd>The file is in a weird half-edited state you'd rather start fresh from. Back it up first (<code>cp .env .env.bak</code>) so you can recover the prior <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> if you need to. <code>gw init</code> on an absent file is a cold install and mints all three secrets fresh.</dd>
      <dt>Don't touch <code>overrides.env</code></dt><dd>Operator-owned. <code>upgrade-env</code> and <code>init</code> never write to it. If you want to opt out of the new secure-by-default behavior, this is where the override lines go.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">After upgrade — verify</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">gw env                       # print resolved env (secrets masked)
gw status                    # /admin/api/snapshot summary
curl -sf http://127.0.0.1:18080/health/hooks | jq    # confirm PIIRedactionHook mode/decrypt_active</pre>
    <p>The <code>config</code> field in <code>/health/hooks</code> will show <code>"mode": "encrypt"</code> and <code>"decrypt_active": true</code> on the default-defaults install. If you opted out via overrides, those values reflect your overrides.</p>
  </section>

