  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Hooks</h2>
    <p>Gateway processes every request through a configurable hook chain. The default chain is enabled out-of-the-box; narrow it via the <code>ENABLED_HOOKS</code> env var (comma-separated allowlist; empty value = all hooks active).</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Default hook chain</h3>
    <div class="gw-docs-table-scroll">
      <table class="gw-table gw-docs-flags-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th scope="col">Hook</th><th scope="col">Kind</th><th scope="col">Default</th><th scope="col">Purpose</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>RequestIDHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled</td><td>Assigns a unique request ID propagated through structured logs and downstream worker headers.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>AuthHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled</td><td>Enforces bearer-token (<code>AUTH_TOKEN</code>) + IP-allowlist (<code>ALLOWED_IPS</code>) when configured. No-op when both are empty (Node parity).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>JSONFormatSteeringHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled</td><td>Appends a hard JSON-steering system-prompt block whenever the request carries a structured-output format (Ollama <code>format:"json"</code> / <code>format:&lt;schema&gt;</code> — Node shim GEN_RULES parity). Work-gated by <code>JSON_FORMAT_STEERING_ENABLED</code> (default <code>true</code>).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>PIIRedactionHook</code></td><td>Pre,Post</td><td>enabled</td><td>Detects and redacts PII in inbound prompts before they reach the upstream worker (Pre). The default mode is <code>encrypt</code>: detected matches become <code>[PII:Entity:base64url(...)]</code> AES-256-GCM tokens before the worker sees them, and the Post hook decrypts those tokens back to plaintext before the client sees the response (transparent round-trip). Set <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false</code> to opt out (the hook stays in the chain but does no work).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>CompressionHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled (inert by default)</td><td>Opt-in transcript compression: shrinks the canonical transcript sent to the worker (blank-line cleanup → stale tool-result truncation → duplicate collapse → local BM25 relevance pruning against the user's latest question). Work-gated by <code>COMPRESSION_ENABLED</code> (default <code>false</code>); per-request overrides via the <code>X-Compression</code> header or a <code>+compress</code>/<code>-compress</code> model-name suffix. See the Context compression section below.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>LoggingHook</code></td><td>Pre,Post</td><td>enabled</td><td>Emits structured request/response log entries (slog JSON). The same instance runs as the last Pre hook and the only Post hook, bridging timings via an internal request-ID map.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">PII redaction</h3>
    <p>PIIRedactionHook is dual-natured: it runs Pre (fourth in the chain, after RequestID, Auth, and JSONFormatSteering) so redacted prompts never reach the upstream worker, and Post (after the worker's response) so encrypt-mode tokens can be decrypted back to plaintext before the client sees the response. <strong>It is on by default with <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt</code> — the worker never sees plaintext PII unless the operator explicitly opts out via <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false</code>.</strong></p>
    <p>Recognizer set: 13 regex recognizers (<code>Email</code>, <code>IPv4</code>, <code>IPv6</code>, <code>SSN</code>, <code>CreditCard</code>, <code>USPhone</code>, <code>SIP_URI</code>, <code>IMEI</code>, <code>IMSI</code>, <code>MSISDN</code>, <code>MAC_ADDRESS</code>, <code>COORDINATES</code>, <code>SITE</code>) plus 2 NER recognizers from <code>jdkato/prose/v2</code> (<code>PERSON</code>, <code>LOCATION</code>) when <code>PII_NER_ENABLED=true</code>. Context-anchored recognizers (<code>IMEI</code>, <code>IMSI</code>, <code>MSISDN</code>, <code>SITE</code>) require a recognizer-specific keyword within ±50 bytes of the match.</p>

    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt><code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED</code></dt><dd>default <code>true</code> — master switch. Set to <code>false</code> to keep the hook in the chain but inert (operator opt-out).</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_REDACTION_MODE</code></dt><dd>default <code>encrypt</code> — one of <code>replace</code> (numbered sentinel per match), <code>mask</code> (partial obfuscation), <code>hash</code> (HMAC-keyed correlation token), <code>drop</code> (matched substring removed entirely), <code>encrypt</code> (AES-256-GCM round-trip — request encrypted, response decrypted by the Post hook before the client sees it).</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_NER_ENABLED</code></dt><dd>default <code>true</code> — master switch for the prose-based PERSON/LOCATION recognizer. When <code>true</code>, the bundled averaged-perceptron model lazy-loads on first request. Set to <code>false</code> to skip the runtime tokenizer/tagger allocation (the ~7 MB binary impact is baked into the build either way). English-only; accuracy is decent on common Western names and major place names but weaker on Asian / multilingual names.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENABLED_ENTITIES</code></dt><dd>default empty (all registered recognizers active) — comma-separated allowlist from <code>Email,IPv4,IPv6,SSN,CreditCard,USPhone,SIP_URI,IMEI,IMSI,MSISDN,MAC_ADDRESS,COORDINATES,SITE,PERSON,LOCATION</code>. <code>PERSON</code> and <code>LOCATION</code> require <code>PII_NER_ENABLED=true</code> to actually fire.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS</code></dt><dd>default empty — per-entity action override map. Shape: <code>Entity:action,Entity:action,…</code> (e.g. <code>Email:encrypt,SSN:drop,PERSON:mask</code>). Listed entities use the named action; unlisted entities fall back to <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE</code>. Allowed actions: <code>replace</code>, <code>mask</code>, <code>hash</code>, <code>drop</code>, <code>encrypt</code>. Unknown entity name or action ⇒ boot error.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_HASH_KEY</code></dt><dd>auto-minted by <code>gw init</code> — REQUIRED when <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=hash</code> (boot error otherwise). HMAC-SHA256 key. Rotating it invalidates prior session correlation tokens.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code></dt><dd>auto-minted by <code>gw init</code> — REQUIRED when encrypt is active anywhere (the default <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt</code>, OR any <code>PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS</code> entry of the form <code>Entity:encrypt</code>); boot error otherwise, naming the env var in the fatal log. Any non-empty string; the gateway derives a 32-byte AES-256-GCM key via SHA-256 at boot. <code>--regenerate-secrets</code> rotates this alongside <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> and <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>. Rotating invalidates every prior encrypted token (decrypt-on-response will fail) — treat as a breaking change for any in-flight round-tripping conversation. Streaming is auto-disabled when encrypt is active (the Pre hook flips <code>Stream=false</code> and adapters re-route to the aggregated path).</dd>
    </dl>

    <p>Detected PII is replaced with bracketed sentinels like <code>[EMAIL_1]</code>, <code>[PHONE_2]</code>, <code>[EMAIL:h-abc12345]</code> (hash mode), or <code>[PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)]</code> (encrypt mode, the default). Square brackets are deliberate — angle-bracketed sentinels like <code>&lt;EMAIL_1&gt;</code> caused kiro-cli to treat them as opening XML tags (see fix 260531-pt8).</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Examples</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block"># Default config — PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true, PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt,
# PII_NER_ENABLED=true, PII_ENCRYPT_KEY auto-minted at install:
#   request:  "Email a@b.com — John Smith called"
#   → worker: "Email [PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)] — [PII:PERSON:base64url(...)] called"
#   response: "Tell [PII:PERSON:base64url(...)] I got [PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)]"
#   → client: "Tell John Smith I got a@b.com"
# Streaming auto-disabled in encrypt mode; adapters re-route to aggregated path.</pre>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=replace
# Numbered sentinels per match per entity:
#   "Email me at a@b.com or c@d.com"
#   → "Email me at [EMAIL_1] or [EMAIL_2]"</pre>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=hash
PII_HASH_KEY=&lt;32+ random bytes, hex or base64&gt;
PII_ENABLED_ENTITIES=Email,SSN
# Same value → same hash sentinel within a key lifetime (correlation
# across requests without leaking the underlying PII):
#   "a@b.com … a@b.com" → "[EMAIL:h-9f3a2c1d] … [EMAIL:h-9f3a2c1d]"</pre>
    <pre class="gw-code-block"># Per-entity action mix — global encrypt, but mask PERSON for human readability
# in audit logs and drop LOCATION entirely from the worker's view:
PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt
PII_ENCRYPT_KEY=&lt;auto-minted; rotate via --regenerate-secrets&gt;
PII_NER_ENABLED=true
PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS=PERSON:mask,LOCATION:drop</pre>

    <p><strong>SENSITIVE:</strong> <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code> writes raw prompts to <code>CHAT_TRACE_FILE</code> <em>before</em> PIIRedactionHook runs. When chat-trace is on, the on-disk file contains unredacted PII — this is why the About page surfaces a SENSITIVE badge whenever <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code>. Turn off in production unless intentionally debugging a request shape.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Context compression (CompressionHook)</h3>
    <p>CompressionHook runs after PIIRedactionHook (it compresses already-redacted text) and before LoggingHook (logs show the transcript actually sent). Pipeline, cheapest first with the budget re-checked between stages: blank-line/trailing-space cleanup → stale tool-result truncation → exact-duplicate collapse → local BM25 lexical relevance pruning against the user's most recent question. Everything runs in-process — no network call or external model. Compression never fails a request: any internal failure forwards the request with whatever stages had already applied.</p>
    <p>Toggle precedence: <code>X-Compression</code> header (accepts <code>1</code>/<code>true</code>/<code>on</code> and <code>0</code>/<code>false</code>/<code>off</code>; other values ignored) &gt; <code>+compress</code>/<code>-compress</code> model-name suffix (e.g. <code>auto+compress</code> — for callers like LangFlow that cannot send headers) &gt; <code>COMPRESSION_ENABLED</code> env default. <code>ENABLED_HOOKS</code> remains the hard kill switch: an explicit allowlist must include <code>CompressionHook</code> or none of the toggles do anything (the dashboard's Compression chip reflects this effective posture).</p>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt><code>COMPRESSION_ENABLED</code></dt><dd>default <code>false</code> — process-wide default; per-request header/suffix overrides win in either direction.</dd>
      <dt><code>COMPRESS_TRIGGER_TOKENS</code></dt><dd>default <code>6000</code> — below this estimated transcript size (UTF-8 bytes/4 heuristic) compression is a no-op.</dd>
      <dt><code>COMPRESS_BUDGET_TOKENS</code></dt><dd>default <code>4000</code> — target size; must be ≤ trigger (boot error otherwise). Best-effort: protected/pinned messages and tool-call carriers are never elided, and stage 4 elides nothing when no message shares a token with the question — a run can end over budget (counted as <code>budget_unmet</code> in <code>/health/hooks</code>).</dd>
      <dt><code>COMPRESS_PROTECT_TAIL</code></dt><dd>default <code>4</code> — the last N messages pass through verbatim. Regardless of this value the system prompt, tool schemas, tool-call pairing, the current inbound turn, and the most recent user question are never modified.</dd>
      <dt><code>COMPRESS_TOOL_KEEP</code></dt><dd>default <code>1200</code> — head+tail bytes kept when middle-truncating stale tool results (bounded 1..4194304).</dd>
    </dl>
    <p>Observability: <code>/health/hooks</code> shows the CompressionHook config plus lifetime counters (<code>runs</code>, <code>tokens_saved_est</code>, <code>budget_unmet</code>); <code>/metrics</code> exposes <code>gw_compress_runs_total</code> and <code>gw_compress_tokens_saved_estimate_total</code>. Known interaction: with PII encrypt mode active, middle-truncation of a stale tool result can clip an embedded ciphertext token (that token then cannot be decrypted in the response; the request still succeeds) — a boot warning is logged whenever encrypt mode is active.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">PII smoke test</h2>
    <p>Every install ships a <code>test-pii</code> script that exercises PII redaction end-to-end. Three scenarios:</p>
    <ul class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><code>diag</code> — print the gateway's PII posture from <code>/health/hooks</code> (mode, encrypt-active, active recognizers, full hook chain). No round-trip.</li>
      <li><code>wire</code> — for each surface, send a <code>"hi"</code> request with <code>stream=true</code> AND <code>stream=false</code> and assert the right <code>Content-Type</code> comes back. The v1.9.0 regression check lives here: streaming requests under <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt</code> must yield <code>text/event-stream</code> (Anthropic / OpenAI) or <code>application/x-ndjson</code> (Ollama), NOT <code>application/json</code>.</li>
      <li><code>pii</code> — send a PII-rich prompt, capture the response, and verify each PII value round-tripped back to plaintext. Proves the encrypt Pre-hook + decrypt Post-hook pair is working end-to-end. Detects ciphertext leaks too (a <code>[PII:Entity:base64url]</code> token in the client-visible response = decrypt failed).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Default scenario runs all three. Exit code 0 means every check passed; 1 means at least one failed.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">macOS / Linux</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">./scripts/test-pii.sh                         # diag + wire + pii against all surfaces
./scripts/test-pii.sh diag                    # PII posture only — no round-trip
./scripts/test-pii.sh wire --surface anthropic # one surface
./scripts/test-pii.sh pii -v                  # verbose: print extracted response text
./scripts/test-pii.sh --auth $TOKEN           # if AUTH_TOKEN is configured
./scripts/test-pii.sh --base http://10.0.0.5:18080  # remote gateway</pre>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Windows (PowerShell)</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">.\scripts\test-pii.ps1
.\scripts\test-pii.ps1 diag
.\scripts\test-pii.ps1 wire -Surface anthropic
.\scripts\test-pii.ps1 pii -Verbose
.\scripts\test-pii.ps1 -Auth $env:AUTH_TOKEN
.\scripts\test-pii.ps1 -Base http://10.0.0.5:18080</pre>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">What each check looks for</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt>diag → hook chain</dt><dd>All 6 registered hooks (RequestIDHook, AuthHook, JSONFormatSteeringHook, PIIRedactionHook, CompressionHook, LoggingHook) present in registration order. Drift means an operator narrowed <code>ENABLED_HOOKS</code>.</dd>
      <dt>diag → PII config</dt><dd>Surfaces <code>enabled</code> / <code>mode</code> / <code>decrypt_active</code> / <code>entities</code> from the running hook's <code>Describe</code> output. <code>decrypt_active=true</code> means encrypt round-trip is on the wire path.</dd>
      <dt>wire → Content-Type</dt><dd>Streaming requests must come back with the streaming content-type. An <code>application/json</code> response on <code>stream=true</code> means the synthetic-SSE fix isn't wired (running an older binary).</dd>
      <dt>pii → no ciphertext leak</dt><dd>The response MUST NOT contain a <code>[PII:Entity:base64url]</code> token. If it does, the Post-hook decrypt failed mid-flow — check the gateway log for <code>pii.decrypt.failed</code> WARN lines.</dd>
      <dt>pii → plaintext present</dt><dd>The known-PII values from the prompt must appear in the response text (proves decrypt actually restored them).</dd>
    </dl>

    <p><strong>Auth note:</strong> if you have <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> configured, pass <code>--auth TOKEN</code> (POSIX) or <code>-Auth TOKEN</code> (PowerShell). The script sets the <code>Authorization: Bearer</code> header on every probe. Without it, AuthHook returns 401 and every check fails.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Troubleshooting — kiro-cli inside WSL on Windows</h2>
    <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> a native Windows gateway works fine when paired with a native Windows kiro-cli, but loses the ACP connection when kiro-cli is run from inside WSL (with <code>KIRO_CMD=wsl.exe</code> or a path under <code>\\wsl$\</code>). The Node-JS gateway didn't have this problem.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Why the Go gateway exposes it (and Node didn't)</h3>
    <p>The data path is multi-layered when kiro-cli runs inside WSL2:</p>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">Go gateway (Windows process)
   ↓ CreateProcess anonymous pipe (Windows kernel)
wsl.exe (Windows binary — thin bridge to LXSS)
   ↓ vsock stdio translation (Windows ↔ Linux pipe FDs)
kiro-cli (Linux process inside the WSL2 lightweight VM)</pre>
    <p>Three things go wrong, any of which can drop the long-running ACP session:</p>
    <ol class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Linux stdio block buffering</strong> — when kiro-cli's stdout is a pipe (not a terminal), glibc defaults to <em>block buffered</em> writes. ACP responses sit inside kiro-cli's buffer until it fills or kiro-cli explicitly flushes. The gateway's blocking read on the other side of the bridge waits forever, the heartbeat times out, the pool reaps the slot.</li>
      <li><strong>Split-brain process tree</strong> — <code>wsl.exe</code> is the only PID Go can see, signal, or kill. The actual kiro-cli is a Linux process the Windows side cannot directly address. <code>Cmd.Process.Kill()</code> kills <code>wsl.exe</code> but may leave kiro-cli as a WSL orphan; conversely, when kiro-cli exits on the Linux side, <code>wsl.exe</code> may not propagate the exit cleanly back to Go's <code>Wait()</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>WSL2 vsock latency</strong> — stdio goes through Hyper-V vsock with internal batching. Cumulative latency under load can exceed the default <code>STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC=30</code> watchdog and trip the idle-timeout.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The Node gateway sidestepped all three: libuv pipes are non-blocking by default (so Linux block-buffering still hurt but Node's event loop kept the connection alive between bursts), and Node had no idle-timeout watchdog at all. Go's <code>os/exec</code> reads are synchronous blocking syscalls on Windows — strict where Node was lenient. WSL2's stdio is lenient-tolerant; the Go strictness exposes the bridge's quirks.</p>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Things to try, in priority order</h3>
    <ol class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li>
        <strong>Disable Linux stdio buffering with <code>stdbuf</code>.</strong> Most likely #1 culprit — fixes the block-buffering case. Add to <code>overrides.env</code>:
        <pre class="gw-code-block">KIRO_CMD=wsl.exe
KIRO_ARGS=--exec /usr/bin/stdbuf -i0 -o0 -e0 /full/path/to/kiro-cli acp</pre>
        <code>stdbuf -i0 -o0 -e0</code> tells glibc to use unbuffered stdin/stdout/stderr for the child. Responses flush the moment they're written. If <code>stdbuf</code> is missing from your distro, install <code>coreutils</code> inside WSL.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Use <code>--exec</code>, not the default wsl invocation.</strong> Without <code>--exec</code>, wsl.exe starts a login shell that then runs kiro-cli. The shell adds its own buffering and complicates signal propagation. <code>--exec</code> replaces the wsl.exe process with kiro-cli directly via execve — one fewer layer, cleaner signal handling.
        <pre class="gw-code-block">KIRO_ARGS=--exec /full/path/to/kiro-cli acp</pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Raise the idle timeout as a band-aid for vsock latency.</strong> Default is 30s — generous on native, marginal across WSL2. If the drop happens reproducibly near the 30s mark, this is your problem:
        <pre class="gw-code-block">STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC=120</pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Switch to TCP if kiro-cli supports it.</strong> If kiro-cli has a socket-listening mode, running it as a TCP server inside WSL and pointing the gateway at <code>127.0.0.1:PORT</code> sidesteps the entire stdio bridge. WSL2 forwards localhost ports, so a Linux-side listener is reachable from the Windows gateway. Cleanest fix but requires kiro-cli support.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Diagnostic data — collect this if the steps above don't fix it</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block"># 1. Confirm current KIRO_* values
gw.ps1 env | Select-String "KIRO"

# 2. Reproduce with DEBUG=true and capture the log around the drop
Add-Content $env:USERPROFILE\.gw\overrides.env "DEBUG=true"
gw.ps1 restart
# (reproduce — send a request)
gw.ps1 logs | Select-Object -Last 50

# 3. Immediately after the connection drop, check WSL — is kiro-cli
#    still alive (bridge break) or did it exit (real kiro death)?
wsl.exe ps aux | findstr kiro

# 4. Capture kiro-cli stderr to a Linux-side file so you can see
#    complaints that never made it across the bridge:
#    KIRO_ARGS=--exec sh -c 'exec /path/to/kiro-cli acp 2&gt;&gt;/tmp/kiro.err'
wsl.exe cat /tmp/kiro.err</pre>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">What the log lines mean</h3>
    <dl class="gw-about-dl">
      <dt><code>pii.redact.done</code> then silence</dt><dd>Gateway sent the redacted request, kiro never replied. <strong>Likely stdio buffering</strong> — try step 1.</dd>
      <dt><code>pool: slot died</code> with no obvious cause</dt><dd>Either kiro-cli exited inside WSL or wsl.exe exited mid-session. <strong>Likely process-tree split-brain</strong> — try step 2; cross-reference with <code>wsl ps</code>.</dd>
      <dt><code>stream.idle_timeout</code></dt><dd>vsock latency exceeded the watchdog threshold. <strong>Likely step 3</strong> — bump the timeout.</dd>
      <dt><code>acp: dispatcher: read EOF</code></dt><dd>The pipe closed unexpectedly. Combine with <code>wsl ps</code> output to figure out which side died first (Linux kiro exited / Windows wsl.exe exited / bridge dropped).</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="gw-h3">Recommended starting config</h3>
    <pre class="gw-code-block">KIRO_CMD=wsl.exe
KIRO_ARGS=--exec /usr/bin/stdbuf -i0 -o0 -e0 /home/&lt;you&gt;/path/to/kiro-cli acp
STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC=120
DEBUG=true</pre>
    <p>If this combination still drops the connection, paste the log lines around the drop + <code>wsl ps</code> output for the diagnostic team. If the root cause turns out to be #2 (split-brain process tree), there's a real gateway-side fix involving Windows job objects + WSL-aware kill semantics that would land in a future release.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Basic admin usage</h2>
    <ul class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Status pill</strong> — green = healthy (pool ready + at least one slot idle), amber = degraded (KIRO_CMD missing or pool starving), red = down (no slots, no recovery in flight).</li>
      <li><strong>Pool slots</strong> — one card per warm kiro-cli subprocess; idle (yellow), busy (purple), or terminated (red) with last-error context.</li>
      <li><strong>Active sessions</strong> — stateful conversation sessions per the session registry; idle &gt; <code>SESSION_TTL_MS</code> are reaped on the next tick.</li>
      <li><strong>Log tail</strong> — pick a source from the dropdown, stream SSE-delivered lines into the table. Use the search box for client-side <code>dataset.raw</code> grep.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="gw-card">
    <h2 class="gw-h2">Troubleshooting</h2>
    <ul class="gw-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Status shows degraded</strong> — usually <code>KIRO_CMD</code> is unset or not on <code>$PATH</code>. Check the Upstream Worker card on <a href="/admin/about">About</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Status shows down</strong> — all pool slots terminated. Inspect the Log tail filtered on <code>pool.acquire</code> / <code>pool.recover</code> for the underlying spawn or ACP error.</li>
      <li><strong>Requests hang for ~120s then time out</strong> — server-side stream-idle watchdog is disabled (<code>STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC=0</code>) and the upstream stalled silently. Re-enable the watchdog (default 30s) and retry.</li>
      <li><strong>"chat trace enabled" warning at startup</strong> — <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code> writes raw prompts to disk at the path shown in <em>Files &amp; paths</em>. Turn off in production unless intentionally debugging.</li>
      <li><strong>Where do logs go?</strong> — structured slog JSON to stdout / stderr by default; set <code>LOG_FILE</code> for a rotated on-disk copy.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</main>{{end}}
